Add a functor that has block-wise lambda definitions, e.g.

3826 else if (iuob)

3836 // At the timing of adding this, this is only Postprocessors... but technically it
3837 // should enable any UO that is a Real Functor to be used as one
3838 // The ternary operator used in getting the functor is there because some UOs
3839 // are threaded and some are not. When a UO is not threaded, we need to add
3840 // the functor from thread 0 as the registered functor for all threads

3843 dynamic_cast<Moose::FunctorBase<Real> *>(uos[uos.size() == 1 ? 0 : tid].get()))

Create a Tag.

Check to see if an exception has occurred on any processor and stop the solve.

Note: Collective on MPI! Must be called simultaneously by all processors!

Also: This will throw a MooseException!

Note: DO NOT CALL THIS IN A THREADED REGION! This is meant to be called just after a threaded section.

◆ checkProblemIntegrity()

virtualinherited

Method called to perform a series of sanity checks before a simulation is run.

This method doesn't return when errors are found, instead it generally calls mooseError() directly.

If a material is specified for any block in the simulation, then all blocks must have a material specified.

unsigned int is necessary to print SubdomainIDs in the statement below

6905 _current_nl_sys->setSolution(soln);
6906 // For now, do not re-compute auxiliary variables. Doing so allows a wild solution increment
6907 // to get to the material models, which may not be able to cope with drastically different
6908 // values. Once more complete dependency checking is in place, auxiliary variables (and
6909 // material properties) will be computed as needed by dampers.
6910 // _aux.compute();
6911 damping = _current_nl_sys->computeDamping(soln, update);
6912
6913 // restore saved solution
6914 _current_nl_sys->setSolution(*_saved_current_solution);
6915 }
6916
6917 return damping;
6918}

Really not a good idea to use this.

It computes just one block of the Jacobian into a smaller matrix. Calling this in a loop is EXTREMELY ineffecient! Try to use computeJacobianBlocks() instead!

precond_systemThe libMesh::system of the preconditioning system
ivarthe block-row of the Jacobian
jvarthe block-column of the Jacobian

6826 // ghosted "soln" and "update" vectors.
6827 // 2.) Call FEProblemBase::computeDamping() with these ghost vectors.
6828 // 3.) Recreate the code in PetscSupport::dampedCheck() to actually update
6829 // the solution vector based on the damping, and set the "changed" flags
6830 // appropriately.
6831
6832 TIME_SECTION("computePostCheck", 2, "Computing Post Check");
6833
6834 // MOOSE's FEProblemBase doesn't update the solution during the
6835 // postcheck, but FEProblemBase-derived classes might.
6836 if (_has_dampers || shouldUpdateSolution())
6837 {
6838 // We need ghosted versions of new_soln and search_direction (the
6839 // ones we get from libmesh/PETSc are PARALLEL vectors. To make
6840 // our lives simpler, we use the same ghosting pattern as the
6841 // system's current_local_solution to create new ghosted vectors.
6842
6843 // Construct zeroed-out clones with the same ghosted dofs as the
6844 // System's current_local_solution.

6846 sys.current_local_solution->zero_clone(),
6847 ghosted_search_direction =
6848 sys.current_local_solution->zero_clone();
6849
6850 // Copy values from input vectors into clones with ghosted values.
6851 *ghosted_solution = new_soln;
6852 *ghosted_search_direction = search_direction;
6853
6854 if (_has_dampers)
6855 {
6856 // Compute the damping coefficient using the ghosted vectors
6857 Real damping = computeDamping(*ghosted_solution, *ghosted_search_direction);
6858
6859 // If some non-trivial damping was computed, update the new_soln
6860 // vector accordingly.
6861 if (damping < 1.0)
6862 {
6863 new_soln = old_soln;
6864 new_soln.add(-damping, search_direction);
6865 changed_new_soln = true;
6866 }
6867 }
6868
6869 if (shouldUpdateSolution())
6870 {
6871 // Update the ghosted copy of the new solution, if necessary.
6872 if (changed_new_soln)
6873 *ghosted_solution = new_soln;
6874
6875 bool updated_solution = updateSolution(new_soln, *ghosted_solution);
6876 if (updated_solution)
6877 changed_new_soln = true;
6878 }
6879 }

6884 _aux->setPreviousNewtonSolution();
6885 }
6886
6887 // MOOSE doesn't change the search_direction

4296 primary_query.condition<AttribPreAux>(type);
4297 else if (group == Moose::POST_AUX)
4298 primary_query.condition<AttribPostAux>(type);
4299
4300 // query everything first to obtain a list of execution groups
4301 std::vector<UserObject *> uos;
4302 primary_query.clone().queryIntoUnsorted(uos);
4303 std::set<int> execution_groups;
4304 for (const auto & uo : uos)
4305 execution_groups.insert(uo->getParam<int>("execution_order_group"));
4306
4307 // iterate over execution order groups
4308 for (const auto execution_group : execution_groups)
4309 {
4310 auto query = primary_query.clone().condition<AttribExecutionOrderGroup>(execution_group);
4311
4312 std::vector<GeneralUserObject *> genobjs;
4313 query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::GeneralUserObject).queryInto(genobjs);
4314
4315 std::vector<UserObject *> userobjs;
4316 query.clone()
4317 .condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::ElementUserObject | Interfaces::SideUserObject |
4318 Interfaces::InternalSideUserObject |
4319 Interfaces::InterfaceUserObject | Interfaces::DomainUserObject)
4320 .queryInto(userobjs);
4321
4322 std::vector<UserObject *> tgobjs;
4323 query.clone()
4324 .condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::ThreadedGeneralUserObject)
4325 .queryInto(tgobjs);
4326
4327 std::vector<UserObject *> nodal;
4328 query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::NodalUserObject).queryInto(nodal);
4329
4330 std::vector<MortarUserObject *> mortar;
4331 query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::MortarUserObject).queryInto(mortar);
4332
4333 if (userobjs.empty() && genobjs.empty() && tgobjs.empty() && nodal.empty() && mortar.empty())
4334 continue;
4335
4336 // Start the timer here since we have at least one active user object
4337 std::string compute_uo_tag = "computeUserObjects(" + Moose::stringify(type) + ")";
4338
4339 // Perform Residual/Jacobian setups
4340 if (type == EXEC_LINEAR)
4341 {
4342 for (auto obj : userobjs)
4343 obj->residualSetup();
4344 for (auto obj : nodal)
4345 obj->residualSetup();
4346 for (auto obj : mortar)
4347 obj->residualSetup();
4348 for (auto obj : tgobjs)
4349 obj->residualSetup();
4350 for (auto obj : genobjs)
4351 obj->residualSetup();
4352 }
4353 else if (type == EXEC_NONLINEAR)
4354 {
4355 for (auto obj : userobjs)
4356 obj->jacobianSetup();
4357 for (auto obj : nodal)
4358 obj->jacobianSetup();
4359 for (auto obj : mortar)
4360 obj->jacobianSetup();
4361 for (auto obj : tgobjs)
4362 obj->jacobianSetup();
4363 for (auto obj : genobjs)
4364 obj->jacobianSetup();
4365 }
4366
4367 for (auto obj : userobjs)
4368 obj->initialize();
4369
4370 // Execute Side/InternalSide/Interface/Elemental/DomainUserObjects
4371 if (!userobjs.empty())
4372 {
4373 // non-nodal user objects have to be run separately before the nodal user objects run
4374 // because some nodal user objects (NodalNormal related) depend on elemental user objects
4375 // :-(
4376 ComputeUserObjectsThread cppt(*this, query);
4377 Threads::parallel_reduce(*_mesh.getActiveLocalElementRange(), cppt);
4378
4379 // There is one instance in rattlesnake where an elemental user object's finalize depends
4380 // on a side user object having been finalized first :-(
4381 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::SideUserObject));
4382 joinAndFinalize(
4383 query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::InternalSideUserObject));
4384 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::InterfaceUserObject));
4385 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::ElementUserObject));
4386 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::DomainUserObject));
4387 }
4388
4389 // if any userobject may have written to variables we need to close the aux solution
4390 for (const auto & uo : userobjs)
4391 if (auto euo = dynamic_cast<const ElementUserObject *>(uo);
4392 euo && euo->hasWritableCoupledVariables())
4393 {
4394 _aux->solution().close();
4395 _aux->system().update();
4396 break;
4397 }
4398
4399 // Execute NodalUserObjects
4400 // BISON has an axial reloc elemental user object that has a finalize func that depends on a
4401 // nodal user object's prev value. So we can't initialize this until after elemental objects
4402 // have been finalized :-(
4403 for (auto obj : nodal)
4404 obj->initialize();
4405 if (query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::NodalUserObject).count() > 0)
4406 {
4407 ComputeNodalUserObjectsThread cnppt(*this, query);
4408 Threads::parallel_reduce(*_mesh.getLocalNodeRange(), cnppt);
4409 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::NodalUserObject));
4410 }
4411
4412 // if any userobject may have written to variables we need to close the aux solution
4413 for (const auto & uo : nodal)
4414 if (auto nuo = dynamic_cast<const NodalUserObject *>(uo);
4415 nuo && nuo->hasWritableCoupledVariables())
4416 {
4417 _aux->solution().close();
4418 _aux->system().update();
4419 break;
4420 }
4421
4422 // Execute MortarUserObjects
4423 {
4424 for (auto obj : mortar)
4425 obj->initialize();
4426 if (!mortar.empty())
4427 {
4428 auto create_and_run_mortar_functors = [this, type, &mortar](const bool displaced)
4429 {
4430 // go over mortar interfaces and construct functors
4431 const auto & mortar_interfaces = getMortarInterfaces(displaced);
4432 for (const auto & mortar_interface : mortar_interfaces)
4433 {
4434 const auto primary_secondary_boundary_pair = mortar_interface.first;
4435 auto mortar_uos_to_execute =
4436 getMortarUserObjects(primary_secondary_boundary_pair.first,
4437 primary_secondary_boundary_pair.second,
4438 displaced,
4439 mortar);
4440 const auto & mortar_generation_object = mortar_interface.second;
4441
4442 auto * const subproblem = displaced
4443 ? static_cast<SubProblem *>(_displaced_problem.get())
4444 : static_cast<SubProblem *>(this);
4445 MortarUserObjectThread muot(mortar_uos_to_execute,
4446 mortar_generation_object,
4447 *subproblem,
4448 *this,
4449 displaced,
4450 subproblem->assembly(0, 0));
4451
4452 auto process_possibly_handleable_exception = [this, type](auto & exception)
4453 {
4454 // When executing on linear we can turn exceptions into residual domain errors, stop
4455 // the solve, and cut the timestep
4456 if (type == EXEC_LINEAR)
4457 setException(exception.what());
4458 else
4459 // Otherwise we don't know what to do
4460 mooseError(
4461 "We caught an exception during computation of mortar user objects outside of "
4462 "residual evaluation. Unfortunately we don't know how to handle this case, "
4463 "so "
4464 "we will abort.");
4465 };
4466 try
4467 {
4468 muot();
4469 }
4470 catch (MooseException & e)
4471 {
4472 process_possibly_handleable_exception(e);
4473 }
4474 catch (libMesh::LogicError & e)
4475 {
4476 process_possibly_handleable_exception(e);
4477 }
4478 catch (MetaPhysicL::LogicError & e)
4479 {
4480 moose::translateMetaPhysicLError(e);
4481 }
4482 checkExceptionAndStopSolve();
4483 }
4484 };
4485
4486 create_and_run_mortar_functors(false);
4487 if (_displaced_problem)
4488 create_and_run_mortar_functors(true);
4489 }
4490 for (auto obj : mortar)
4491 obj->finalize();
4492 }
4493
4494 // Execute threaded general user objects
4495 for (auto obj : tgobjs)
4496 obj->initialize();
4497 std::vector<GeneralUserObject *> tguos_zero;
4498 query.clone()
4499 .condition<AttribThread>(0)
4500 .condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::ThreadedGeneralUserObject)
4501 .queryInto(tguos_zero);
4502 for (auto obj : tguos_zero)
4503 {
4504 std::vector<GeneralUserObject *> tguos;
4505 auto q = query.clone()
4506 .condition<AttribName>(obj->name())
4507 .condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::ThreadedGeneralUserObject);
4508 q.queryInto(tguos);
4509
4510 ComputeThreadedGeneralUserObjectsThread ctguot(*this);
4511 Threads::parallel_reduce(GeneralUserObjectRange(tguos.begin(), tguos.end()), ctguot);
4512 joinAndFinalize(q);
4513 }
4514
4515 // Execute general user objects
4516 joinAndFinalize(query.clone().condition<AttribInterfaces>(Interfaces::GeneralUserObject), true);
4517 }
4518}

◆ declareManagedRestartableDataWithContext()

template<typename T , typename... Args>
Restartable::ManagedValue< T > Restartable::declareManagedRestartableDataWithContext ( const std::string &  data_name,
void *  context,
Args &&...  args 
)
protectedinherited

Declares a piece of "managed" restartable data and initialize it.

Here, "managed" restartable data means that the caller can destruct this data upon destruction of the return value of this method. Therefore, this ManagedValue<T> wrapper should survive after the final calls to dataStore() for it. That is... at the very end.

This is needed for objects whose destruction ordering is important, and enables natural c++ destruction in reverse construction order of the object that declares it.

See delcareRestartableData and declareRestartableDataWithContext for more information.

◆ getEvaluableElementRange()

const ConstElemRange & FEProblemBase::getEvaluableElementRange ( )
inherited

In general, {evaluable elements} >= {local elements} U {algebraic ghosting elements}.

That is, the number of evaluable elements does NOT necessarily equal to the number of local and algebraic ghosting elements. For example, if using a Lagrange basis for all variables, if a non-local, non-algebraically-ghosted element is surrounded by neighbors which are local or algebraically ghosted, then all the nodal (Lagrange) degrees of freedom associated with the non-local, non-algebraically-ghosted element will be evaluable, and hence that element will be considered evaluable.

getNonlinearEvaluableElementRange() returns the evaluable element range based on the nonlinear system dofmap; getAuxliaryEvaluableElementRange() returns the evaluable element range based on the auxiliary system dofmap; getEvaluableElementRange() returns the element range that is evaluable based on both the nonlinear dofmap and the auxliary dofmap.

1053 transfer->setCurrentDirection(Transfer::DIRECTION::TO_MULTIAPP);
1054 transfer->initialSetup();
1055 }
1056
1057 // Call initialSetup on the MultiAppTransfers to be executed on FROM_MULTIAPP
1058 const auto & from_multi_app_objects = _from_multi_app_transfers.getActiveObjects();
1059 for (const auto & transfer : from_multi_app_objects)
1060 {
1061 transfer->setCurrentDirection(Transfer::DIRECTION::FROM_MULTIAPP);
1062 transfer->initialSetup();
1063 }
1064
1065 // Call initialSetup on the MultiAppTransfers to be executed on BETWEEN_MULTIAPP
1066 const auto & between_multi_app_objects = _between_multi_app_transfers.getActiveObjects();
1067 for (const auto & transfer : between_multi_app_objects)
1068 {
1069 transfer->setCurrentDirection(Transfer::DIRECTION::BETWEEN_MULTIAPP);
1070 transfer->initialSetup();
1071 }
1072 }
1073
1074 if (_boundary_restricted_node_integrity_check)
1075 {
1076 TIME_SECTION("BoundaryRestrictedNodeIntegrityCheck", 5);
1077
1078 // check that variables are defined along boundaries of boundary restricted nodal objects
1079 ConstBndNodeRange & bnd_nodes = *mesh().getBoundaryNodeRange();
1080 BoundaryNodeIntegrityCheckThread bnict(*this, uo_query);
1081 Threads::parallel_reduce(bnd_nodes, bnict);
1082
1083 // Nodal bcs aren't threaded
1084 const auto & node_to_elem_map = _mesh.nodeToActiveSemilocalElemMap();
1085 for (const auto & bnode : bnd_nodes)
1086 {
1087 const auto boundary_id = bnode->_bnd_id;
1088 const Node * const node = bnode->_node;
1089
1090 if (node->processor_id() != this->processor_id())
1091 continue;
1092
1093 // Only check vertices. Variables may not be defined on non-vertex nodes (think first order
1094 // Lagrange on a second order mesh) and user-code can often handle that
1095 const Elem * const an_elem =
1096 _mesh.getMesh().elem_ptr(libmesh_map_find(node_to_elem_map, node->id()).front());
1097 if (!an_elem->is_vertex(an_elem->get_node_index(node)))
1098 continue;
1099
1100 const auto & bnd_name = _mesh.getBoundaryName(boundary_id);
1101
1102 for (auto & nl : _nl)
1103 {
1104 const auto & nodal_bcs = nl->getNodalBCWarehouse();
1105 if (!nodal_bcs.hasBoundaryObjects(boundary_id, 0))
1106 continue;
1107
1108 const auto & bnd_objects = nodal_bcs.getBoundaryObjects(boundary_id, 0);
1109 for (const auto & bnd_object : bnd_objects)
1110 // Skip if this object uses geometric search because coupled variables may be defined on
1111 // paired boundaries instead of the boundary this node is on
1112 if (!bnd_object->requiresGeometricSearch() &&
1113 bnd_object->checkVariableBoundaryIntegrity())
1114 {
1115 std::set<MooseVariableFieldBase *> vars_to_omit = {
1116 &static_cast<MooseVariableFieldBase &>(
1117 const_cast<MooseVariableBase &>(bnd_object->variable()))};
1118
1119 boundaryIntegrityCheckError(
1120 *bnd_object, bnd_object->checkAllVariables(*node, vars_to_omit), bnd_name);
1121 }
1122 }
1123 }
1124 }
1125
1126 if (_boundary_restricted_elem_integrity_check)
1127 {
1128 TIME_SECTION("BoundaryRestrictedElemIntegrityCheck", 5);
1129
1130 // check that variables are defined along boundaries of boundary restricted elemental objects
1131 ConstBndElemRange & bnd_elems = *mesh().getBoundaryElementRange();
1132 BoundaryElemIntegrityCheckThread beict(*this, uo_query);
1133 Threads::parallel_reduce(bnd_elems, beict);
1134 }
1135
1136 if (!_app.isRecovering())
1137 {
1138 execTransfers(EXEC_INITIAL);
1139
1140 bool converged = execMultiApps(EXEC_INITIAL);
1141 if (!converged)
1142 mooseError("failed to converge initial MultiApp");
1143
1144 // We'll backup the Multiapp here
1145 backupMultiApps(EXEC_INITIAL);
1146
1147 for (THREAD_ID tid = 0; tid < n_threads; tid++)
1148 reinitScalars(tid);
1149
1150 execute(EXEC_INITIAL);
1151
1152 // The FEProblemBase::execute method doesn't call all the systems on EXEC_INITIAL, but it does
1153 // set/unset the current flag. Therefore, this resets the current flag to EXEC_INITIAL so that
1154 // subsequent calls (e.g., executeControls) have the proper flag.
1155 setCurrentExecuteOnFlag(EXEC_INITIAL);
1156 }
1157
1158 // Here we will initialize the stateful properties once more since they may have been updated
1159 // during initialSetup by calls to computeProperties.
1160 //
1161 // It's really bad that we don't allow this during restart. It means that we can't add new
1162 // stateful materials
1163 // during restart. This is only happening because this _has_ to be below initial userobject
1164 // execution.
1165 // Otherwise this could be done up above... _before_ restoring restartable data... which would
1166 // allow you to have
1167 // this happen during restart. I honestly have no idea why this has to happen after initial user
1168 // object computation.
1169 // THAT is something we should fix... so I've opened this ticket: #5804
1170 if (!_app.isRecovering() && !_app.isRestarting() &&
1171 (_material_props.hasStatefulProperties() || _bnd_material_props.hasStatefulProperties() ||
1172 _neighbor_material_props.hasStatefulProperties()))
1173 {
1174 TIME_SECTION("computeMaterials", 2, "Computing Initial Material Properties");
1175
1176 initElementStatefulProps(*_mesh.getActiveLocalElementRange(), true);
1177 }
1178
1179 // Control Logic
1180 executeControls(EXEC_INITIAL);
1181
1182 // Scalar variables need to reinited for the initial conditions to be available for output
1183 for (unsigned int tid = 0; tid < n_threads; tid++)
1184 reinitScalars(tid);
1185
1186 if (_displaced_mesh)
1187 _displaced_problem->syncSolutions();
1188
1189 // Writes all calls to _console from initialSetup() methods
1190 _app.getOutputWarehouse().mooseConsole();
1191
1192 if (_requires_nonlocal_coupling)
1193 {
1194 setNonlocalCouplingMatrix();
1195 for (THREAD_ID tid = 0; tid < n_threads; ++tid)
1196 for (auto & assembly : _assembly[tid])
1197 assembly->initNonlocalCoupling();
1198 }
1199
1200 {
1201 TIME_SECTION("lineSearchInitialSetup", 5, "Initializing Line Search");
1202
1203 if (_line_search)
1204 _line_search->initialSetup();
1205 }
1206
1207 // Perform Reporter get/declare check
1208 _reporter_data.check();
1209
1210 // We do this late to allow objects to get late restartable data
1211 if (_app.isRestarting() || _app.isRecovering() || _force_restart)
1212 _app.finalizeRestore();
1213
1214 setCurrentExecuteOnFlag(EXEC_NONE);
1215}

◆ needBoundaryMaterialOnSide()

bool FEProblemBase::needBoundaryMaterialOnSide ( BoundaryID  bnd_id,
const THREAD_ID  tid 
)
inherited

These methods are used to determine whether stateful material properties need to be stored on internal sides.

There are five situations where this may be the case: 1) DGKernels 2) IntegratedBCs 3)InternalSideUserObjects 4)ElementalAuxBCs 5)InterfaceUserObjects

Method 1:

Parameters
bnd_idthe boundary id for which to see if stateful material properties need to be stored
tidthe THREAD_ID of the caller
Returns
Boolean indicating whether material properties need to be stored

Method 2:

Parameters
subdomain_idthe subdomain id for which to see if stateful material properties need to be stored
tidthe THREAD_ID of the caller
Returns
Boolean indicating whether material properties need to be stored

Emits an error prefixed with the file and line number of the given param (from the input file) along with the full parameter path+name followed by the given args as the message.

1235 if (_displaced_mesh)

1237
1238 for (MooseIndex(_num_grid_steps) i = 0; i < _num_grid_steps; ++i)
1239 {
1240 if (_displaced_problem)
1241 // If the DisplacedProblem is active, undisplace the DisplacedMesh in preparation for
1242 // refinement. We can't safely refine the DisplacedMesh directly, since the Hilbert keys
1243 // computed on the inconsistenly-displaced Mesh are different on different processors,
1244 // leading to inconsistent Hilbert keys. We must do this before the undisplaced Mesh is
1245 // coarsensed, so that the element and node numbering is still consistent. We also have to
1246 // make sure this is done during every step of coarsening otherwise different partitions
1247 // will be generated for the reference and displaced meshes (even for replicated)
1248 _displaced_problem->undisplaceMesh();
1249
1250 mesh_refinement.uniformly_coarsen();
1251 if (_displaced_mesh)
1252 displaced_mesh_refinement->uniformly_coarsen();
1253
1254 // Mark this as an intermediate change because we do not yet want to reinit_systems. E.g. we
1255 // need things to happen in the following order for the undisplaced problem:
1256 // u1) EquationSystems::reinit_solutions. This will restrict the solution vectors and then
1257 // contract the mesh
1258 // u2) MooseMesh::meshChanged. This will update the node/side lists and other
1259 // things which needs to happen after the contraction
1260 // u3) GeometricSearchData::reinit. Once the node/side lists are updated we can perform our
1261 // geometric searches which will aid in determining sparsity patterns
1262 //
1263 // We do these things for the displaced problem (if it exists)
1264 // d1) EquationSystems::reinit. Restrict the displaced problem vector copies and then contract
1265 // the mesh. It's safe to do a full reinit with the displaced because there are no
1266 // matrices that sparsity pattern calculations will be conducted for
1267 // d2) MooseMesh::meshChanged. This will update the node/side lists and other
1268 // things which needs to happen after the contraction
1269 // d3) UpdateDisplacedMeshThread::operator(). Re-displace the mesh using the *displaced*
1270 // solution vector copy because we don't know the state of the reference solution vector.
1271 // It's safe to use the displaced copy because we are outside of a non-linear solve,
1272 // and there is no concern about differences between solution and current_local_solution
1273 // d4) GeometricSearchData::reinit. With the node/side lists updated and the mesh
1274 // re-displaced, we can perform our geometric searches, which will aid in determining the
1275 // sparsity pattern of the matrix held by the libMesh::ImplicitSystem held by the
1276 // NonlinearSystem held by this
1277 meshChangedHelper(/*intermediate_change=*/true);
1278 }
1279
1280 // u4) Now that all the geometric searches have been done (both undisplaced and displaced),
1281 // we're ready to update the sparsity pattern
1282 es().reinit_systems();
1283 }
